<DOC><DOCNO> AP880321-0254 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-21-88 0747EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Koppers     03-21 0200</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Koppers,0208</SECOND><HEAD>Beazer-Shearson Sweetens Offer For Koppers To $56 A Share From $45</HEAD><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Koppers Co.'s board of directors will considera sweetened buyout offer totaling about $1.5 billion from a groupled by British investor Brian Beazer and the firm Shearson LehmanHutton Inc., the company says.   The new offer disclosed Sunday of $56 for each of Koppers'roughly 27.2 million common shares outstanding tops the group'sinitial $45 a share offer that Koppers rejected as inadequate lastweek.   Koppers stock rose 12{ cents to $53.75 a share Friday in NewYork Stock Exchange composite trading.   Charles R. Pullin, Koppers chairman, said that in addition toconsidering the sweetened offer the construction materials andchemical company would continue exploring ways to enhanceshareholder values.   In rejecting the investor group's initial offer, Koppers' boardauthorized management to examine defensive alterantives that mightinclude a recapitalization plan under which shareholders wouldreceive a substantial dividend payment while retaining equity inthe company.   Pullin also reiterated a disclosure made last week in aSecurities and Exchange Commission filing that Koppers was engagedin discussions with third parties regarding the possible sale ofthe company's construction materials and services businesses.</TEXT></DOC>